[[ファイル:Japanese crest daki Myouga.svg|thumb|160px|right|{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shrine crest|1=UNKNOWN}} "{{ill|lt=myōga crest|Q11617244|qid=Q11617244|lt=Daki-myōga|1=Myōga mon}}"]]
'''Nahaka Shrine''' (なはかじんじゃ/なばかじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Ōtsu|Q202907|qid=Q202907|1=Ōtsu}}, {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|qid=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, and its former {{ill|lt=modern shrine rank system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=shrine rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Prefectural Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
'''Principal deity'''
* '''{{ill|lt=Futodama|Q11059539|qid=Q11059539|qid=Q11059539|lt=Ame-no-Futodama-no-Mikoto|1=Futodama}}'''

'''Accompanying deity'''
* {{ill|lt=Ochiwake-no-Mikoto|Q0|qid=Q0|lt=Ochiwake-no-Mikoto|1=Ochiwake-no-Mikoto}}

Until the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Meiji period|1=Meiji era|qid=Q3125096}}, the principal deity was said to be {{ill|qid=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama|Q3080728|qid=Q3080728|qid=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto|1=Ukanomitama}}.

=== History ===
According to shrine tradition, Ame-no-Futodama-no-Mikoto descended here and was enshrined from ancient times. A deer appeared and carried rice seedlings to help the now-elderly deity’s farming work; this is said to be origin of shrine/place name “Noka (Nahaka/Nōka).” Nearby remain the Noka kofun cluster and Hōkō-ji kofun cluster.

In {{ill|lt=851|Q29966|qid=Q29966|1=851}} ({{ill|lt=Ninju|Q1373077|qid=Q1373077|1=Ninju}} 1), after {{ill|lt=Abo no Imao|Q11657229|qid=Q11657229|lt=Otsuki no Sukune Imao|1=Abo no Imao}} received Ogoto-shō, this shrine and {{ill|lt=Ogoto Shrine (Ōtsu)|Q11659231|qid=Q11659231|lt=Ogoto Shrine|1=Ogoto Shrine (Otsu)}} were revered as clan shrines of the {{ill|lt=Otsuki clan|Q11462133|qid=Q11462133|1=Ozuki clan}}. Their clan temple {{ill|lt=Hōkō-ji (Ōtsu)|Q11555028|qid=Q11555028|lt=Hōkō-ji|1=Hōkō-ji Temple}} became this shrine’s {{ill|lt=bettō temple|Q11396755|qid=Q11396755|1=Bettō-ji}}.

In the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}' '{{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}' (Enchō 5, {{ill|lt=927|Q30470|qid=Q30470|1=927}}), it appears in {{ill|lt=Shiga District|Q7496289|qid=Q7496289|1=Shiga District, Shiga}} of {{ill|lt=Ōmi Province|Q843882|qid=Q843882|1=Ōmi Province}} as “Nahaka Shrine,” and is ranked {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}.

In {{ill|lt=1571|Q6666|qid=Q6666|1=1571}} ({{ill|lt=Genki|Q1145064|qid=Q1145064|1=Genki (era)}} 2), buildings were burned in {{ill|lt=Oda Nobunaga|Q171411|qid=Q171411|1=Oda Nobunaga}}’s {{ill|lt=Siege of Mount Hiei (1571)|Q10748887|qid=Q10748887|1=Siege of Mount Hiei}}, and rebuilt in {{ill|lt=1607|Q6756|qid=Q6756|1=1607}} ({{ill|lt=Keichō|Q1328185|qid=Q1328185|1=Keichō}} 12).

In October {{ill|lt=1876|Q7766|qid=Q7766|1=1876}} (Meiji 9), it was ranked {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}} under the modern shrine rank system, promoted to {{ill|lt=Gōsha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}} in January {{ill|lt=1895|Q7844|qid=Q7844|1=1895}}, then to {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Prefectural Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}} in May {{ill|lt=1902|Q2043|qid=Q2043|1=1902}}.

=== Precincts ===
The main shrine is called “Lower Shrine,” versus Nahaka Aramitama Shrine called “Upper Shrine.”

=== Sessha and massha ===
